body:
This is a normal error message in certain cases. It should not come up by default but it may come up if you force NUnit to do something like trying to run a 4.5 assembly under 2.0.

What command line was used to result in this message?

`nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll --noresult --framework=4.0 --workers=10 --verbose`
But it works under NUnit 2.6.4:
`nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll /framework=4.0`

HelloWorld.Tests.NUnit2 (mscorlib, Version=4.0.0.0)
ref to
    nunit.framework, Version=2.6.4.14350 (mscorlib, Version=2.0.0.0)

nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.NUnit2.dll /framework=4.0
ok
nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.NUnit2.dll /framework=2.0
failed
nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.NUnit2.dll /framework=4.5
ok
nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.NUnit2.dll
Execution Runtime: net-3.5
ok

HelloWorld.Tests (mscorlib, Version=4.0.0.0)
ref to
    nunit.framework, Version=3.0.5610.33196 (mscorlib, Version=2.0.0.0)

nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll --framework=4.0
failed

nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll --framework=2.0
failed

nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll --framework=4.5
failed

nunit-console.exe HelloWorld.Tests.dll
ok

nunit-agent.exe.config has no changes
@NikolayPianikov, thanks, that is exactly what we needed. Looks like a bug to me :beetle:

https://github.com/NikolayPianikov/HelloWorld.git
Could you fork it

PS: May be we add some regression and integration tests for general cases

I'm able to replicate this using NUnit's own tests, which makes it simpler. 

I think the problem is with the user of --framework=4.0 rather than --framework=net-4.0. Could you try that in your environment?

rename.from: Test is failed when I run it with specified framework version
rename.to: TestAgency does not launch agent process correctly if runtime type is not specified (i.e. v4.0)

body: Changed title to reflect what I have found. When no runtime is specified, the TestAgency has different code to launch agent under .NET versus Mono. If only the version is specified, it should pick one - the one under which it is currently running, I think.
